+## Plugin System Design
+
+### Plugin Lifecycle
+
+Every plugin moves through a well-defined state machine:
+
+```
+          ┌──────────────────┐
+          │    INACTIVE      │
+          └────────┬─────────┘
+                   │ register / load
+                   ▼
+          ┌──────────────────┐
+          │   ACTIVATING     │ ←── activate() called
+          └────────┬─────────┘
+                   │ success          ┌──────────────┐
+                   ▼                  │              │
+          ┌──────────────────┐   ┌────┤    ERROR     │
+          │     ACTIVE       │   │    │              │
+          └────────┬─────────┘   │    └──────────────┘
+                   │             │
+                   ▼             │
+          ┌──────────────────┐   │
+          │  DEACTIVATING    │───┘
+          └────────┬─────────┘
+                   ▼
+          ┌──────────────────┐
+          │    INACTIVE      │
+          └──────────────────┘
+```
+
+States are tracked via the `PluginState` schema (`"inactive" | "activating" | "active" | "deactivating" | "error"`).
+
+### Manifest Format
+
+Plugins declare themselves via a `package.json` containing an `"omnicode"`, `"omnicode-plugin"`, or `"plugin"` marker field. The `PluginManifest` schema validates the structure:
+
+```typescript
+// From packages/omnicode-plugin/src/types.ts
+
+export interface PluginManifest {
+  /** Unique plugin identifier (branded string). */
+  id: PluginId;
+  /** Human-readable name. */
+  name: string;
+  /** Semantic version. */
+  version: string;
+  /** Optional description. */
+  description?: string;
+  /** Author string (npm-style). */
+  author?: string;
+  /** SPDX license identifier. */
+  license?: string;
+  /** Entry point relative to plugin directory. */
+  main: string;                              // default: "index.js"
+  /** Hooks that trigger automatic activation. */
+  activationHooks?: PluginHook[];
+  /** What this plugin contributes to OmniCode. */
+  contributes?: {
+    agents?: AgentContribution[];            // Custom AI agents
+    routes?: RouteContribution[];            // UI navigation targets
+    providers?: ProviderContribution[];      // Git provider backends
+    paints?: PaintContribution[];            // UI decorations
+  };
+}
+```
+
+#### Example Plugin `package.json`
+
+```json
+{
+  "name": "my-code-quality-plugin",
+  "version": "0.1.0",
+  "omnicode": {
+    "id": "my-code-quality",
+    "main": "dist/index.js",
+    "activationHooks": ["pr:created"],
+    "contributes": {
+      "agents": [
+        { "id": "style-checker", "name": "Style Checker", "capabilities": ["code-review"] }
+      ],
+      "routes": [
+        { "id": "quality-dashboard", "label": "Quality", "path": "/quality",
+          "navigation": "sidebar", "component": "QualityDashboard" }
+      ],
+      "providers": [
+        { "id": "gitlab-self", "name": "GitLab Self-Hosted", "type": "gitlab",
+          "baseUrl": "https://gitlab.mycompany.com", "authType": "token" }
+      ]
+    }
+  }
+}
+```
+
+### Plugin Discovery & Loading
+
+The `PluginLoader` (`packages/omnicode-plugin/src/loader.ts`) handles discovery:
+
+```
+discoverPlugins(dirs: string[]) → DiscoveryResult
+  │
+  ├─ For each directory, read package.json
+  ├─ Check for plugin marker field ("omnicode" | "omnicode-plugin" | "plugin")
+  ├─ Build and validate PluginManifest via Schema.decodeUnknownSync
+  └─ Return { plugins: DiscoPlugin[], errors: DiscoveryError[] }
+```
+
+The `PluginRegistry` (`packages/omnicode-plugin/src/registry.ts`) manages the full lifecycle:
+
+```typescript
+export interface PluginRegistry {
+  register(plugin: OmniCodePlugin, manifest: PluginManifest, dir?: string): void;
+  unregister(pluginId: string): Promise<void>;
+  load(disco: DiscoPlugin): Promise<void>;
+  loadAll(dirs: string[]): Promise<{ loaded: number; errors: string[] }>;
+  activate(pluginId: string): Promise<void>;
+  deactivate(pluginId: string): Promise<void>;
+  get(pluginId: string): LoadedPlugin | undefined;
+  list(): LoadedPlugin[];
+  getAgents(): AgentContribution[];
+  getRoutes(): RouteContribution[];
+  getProviders(): ProviderContribution[];
+  getPaints(): PaintContribution[];
+}
+```
+
+### Extension Points
+
+Plugins contribute to four categories of extension points:
+
+#### 1. Navigation Targets (`NavigationTarget`)
+
+| Target | Location | Use Case |
+|--------|----------|----------|
+| `"sidebar"` | Left sidebar nav | Primary plugin pages (e.g., "Issues", "Agents") |
+| `"top"` | Top toolbar | Quick-action buttons |
+| `"settings"` | Settings panel section | Configuration forms |
+| `"dropdown"` | User menu dropdown | Account-level actions |
+
+Each route contribution specifies its target via the `RouteContribution` schema:
+
+```typescript
+export interface RouteContribution {
+  id: string;
+  label: string;
+  icon?: string;
+  path: string;          // TanStack Router path
+  component: string;     // React component identifier
+  panel?: string;        // Optional parent panel
+  navigation: "sidebar" | "top" | "settings" | "dropdown";
+}
+```
+
+#### 2. Provider Contributions (`ProviderContribution`)
+
+Plugins can add new Git hosting provider backends:
+
+```typescript
+export interface ProviderContribution {
+  id: string;
+  name: string;
+  type: "github" | "gitlab" | "bitbucket" | "gitea" | "custom";
+  baseUrl: string;
+  apiVersion?: string;
+  authType: "token" | "oauth" | "basic" | "none";
+  capabilities?: string[];
+}
+```
+
+#### 3. Paint Contributions (`PaintContribution`)
+
+Paints are UI decorations injected at named DOM targets:
+
+```typescript
+export interface PaintContribution {
+  id: string;
+  target: string;              // DOM target identifier
+  style?: string;              // CSS or stylesheet URL
+  position: "before" | "after" | "replace" | "append" | "prepend";
+  component: string;           // React component identifier
+}
+```
+
+Positions define how the paint integrates:
+
+| Position | Behavior |
+|----------|----------|
+| `"before"` | Render component before the target element |
+| `"after"` | Render component after the target element |
+| `"replace"` | Replace the target element entirely |
+| `"append"` | Append component as last child of target |
+| `"prepend"` | Prepend component as first child of target |
+
+### Hook System
+
+The `HookEmitter` (`packages/omnicode-plugin/src/hooks.ts`) provides a publish-subscribe system for plugin lifecycle events.
+
+#### Supported Hooks
+
+| Hook | Context Type | Fired When |
+|------|-------------|-----------|
+| `"pr:created"` | `PrCreatedContext` | A pull request is opened |
+| `"pr:reviewed"` | `PrReviewedContext` | A PR review is submitted |
+| `"issue:created"` | `IssueCreatedContext` | A new issue is filed |
+| `"issue:assigned"` | `IssueAssignedContext` | An issue is assigned |
+| `"agent:before_run"` | `AgentBeforeRunContext` | Before an agent executes |
+| `"agent:after_run"` | `AgentAfterRunContext` | After an agent completes |
+
+#### Hook Registration
+
+Plugins receive a `PluginContext` during activation with methods:
+
+```typescript
+export interface PluginContext {
+  readonly manifest: PluginManifest;
+  onHook<H extends PluginHook>(hook: H, handler: HookHandler<H>): void;
+  offHook<H extends PluginHook>(hook: H, handler: HookHandler<H>): void;
+  emit<H extends PluginHook>(hook: H, context: PluginHookContext[H]): Promise<void>;
+  log(level: "debug" | "info" | "warn" | "error", message: string, data?: unknown): void;
+}
+```
+
+#### Hook Execution Semantics
+
+- Handlers execute in **priority order** (higher priority first, default `0`).
+- Errors from individual handlers are caught and logged but **do not prevent other handlers** from running.
+- Hooks are **async** — the emitter awaits each handler in sequence.
+- All hooks are **local** to the running OmniCode instance (no cross-process hook distribution).
+
+### Security Model
+
+1. **Sandboxed Module Loading** — Plugins are loaded via dynamic `import()` which respects the host's module isolation. Plugin code runs in the same Node.js process as the server but should be treated as untrusted.
+2. **Capability-Based Contributions** — Plugins declare what they contribute in their manifest. The registry only exposes declared contributions to the host.
+3. **Activation Hooks** — Plugins can declare `activationHooks` that gate their activation to specific events, preventing unnecessary code execution.
+4. **Context-Limited API** — The `PluginContext` provided to `activate()` exposes only hook registration and logging — plugins have no direct access to filesystem, network, or other services unless explicitly provided.
+5. **Plugin Marker Required** — Only directories with a recognized plugin marker in `package.json` are scanned. This prevents accidental loading of arbitrary packages.
+
